	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Agricultural dimensions of WTO Trade Policy Review of Benin, Burkina Faso and Mali</h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 December 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The WTO has published its Trade Policy Review of Benin, Burkina Faso and Mali. In the Secretariat report, the WTO notes that only a small share of these countries’ exports to the EU and USA take advantage of the trade preferences under offer. As least developed countries (LDCs) that are non-signatories of an EPA, the most preferential EU trade regime for which the three countries have been eligible since January 2008 is the ‘Everything But Arms’ (EBA) initiative. Yet only a small share of exports during the year 2008 actually entered the European market under this regime. The highest proportion was recorded by Benin, with 36.4% (€77.9 million) entering duty free under EBA, while 46% were admitted under the standard most favoured nation (MFN) regime to which all WTO members are entitled, and under which imports from other developed countries enter the European market; the remainder could not be allocated owing to statistical problems. For Burkina Faso, only 5.4% entered the EU market under EBA, while over 73% entered with MFN treatment. The proportion in the case of Mali was even smaller: 4% entering duty free under EBA and 60.6% entering under MFN treatment (with the remaining 32.6% being unallocated).</p><p>All three states are also eligible for the USA’s African Growth and Opportunity Act (AGOA). Yet none of the USA’s imports from Benin in 2008 entered under AGOA. About 10% of total US imports from Burkina Faso (US$59,000) benefited from AGOA. In the case of Mali, the share was 5% (US$261,000).</p><p>The exports of two of the three countries are dominated by agriculture, predominantly raw cotton. According to the WTO reports, cotton accounted in 2008 for 37% of Benin’s total exports (having dropped from 68% in 2003), and 75% of Burkina Faso’s. Mali has gold, so cotton accounted for only 14% of its total exports (but for over half of its non-gold exports). Since raw cotton faces generally low tariffs in many markets, this may account for the low apparent utilisation of trade preferences. Since the EU’s MFN tariff on raw cotton is zero, there is no need for traders to register imports under EBA.</p><p>The low preference utilisation may simply reflect a lack of export diversification (into goods for which preferences are more useful commercially because MFN tariffs are high). This lack of diversification in Africa is the subject of a new report by the UN and NEPAD. Based on five case studies in Angola, Benin, Kenya, South Africa, and Tunisia, the report finds that ‘diversification ... remains limited in most African countries, with only a few success stories.’ This ‘dependence on too few export commodities and one or two sectors ... makes many countries vulnerable to fluctuations in commodity prices, demand and extreme weather events such as droughts and floods.’ The report also recognises that ‘many challenges arise when pursuing a diversification strategy’, with major investments needed in human resources and infrastructure. Nonetheless, it is optimistic that the foundations are in place to support a long-term strategy to diversify. As a report from CIRAD shows, many organisations are already working to promote this goal.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>WTO, ‘Trade Policy Review: Benin, Burkina Faso and Mali’, 4 and 6 October 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp336_e.htm" target="_self">http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp336_e.htm</a></p><p>UN Office of the Special Adviser on Africa and NEPAD, ‘Economic diversification in Africa: A review of selected countries’, October 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/library_detail.php?library_detail_id=5457&amp;doc_language=Both" target="_self">http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/library_detail.php?library_detail_id...</a></p><p>CIRAD, ‘Quand la recherche revisite des produits traditionnels africains’, on a European project to add value to traditional African products for marketing in Africa and Europe, 21 October 2010 (in French)</p><p>
<a href="http://www.cirad.fr/actualites/toutes-les-actualites/articles/2010/science/produits-traditionnels-africains" target="_self">http://www.cirad.fr/actualites/toutes-les-actualites/articles/2010/scien...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The main international trade problem as perceived by the three countries covered by the WTO Trade Policy Review is not barriers to their exports, but subsidies by richer export competitors. This is why, together with Chad, they are active in the WTO as the C4 group of cotton farmers which has adopted a common position in the Sectoral Initiative on Cotton to request, among other things, that Members remove any domestic production support measures and export subsidies for cotton. In October 2009, they launched what the WTO Report calls ‘a pressing appeal’ to WTO Members for a rapid, effective and global resumption of the Doha negotiations, with the cotton issue being taken up as ‘an early harvest’ (see <i>Agritrade </i>article ‘
<a href="http://agritrade.cta.int/en/Commodities/Cotton-sector/News" target="_self">ACP resolution on the WTO</a>’, December 2009).</p><p>This call to action on export subsidies is directed to the same OECD states that offer trade preferences and ‘aid for trade’. It underlines the point that all three of these policy areas are linked, and that action on one can easily be undermined by inaction under the others. The fact that the exports of all three are dominated by goods for which preferences are irrelevant (since they are raw material inputs into other countries’ production and, hence, face few import barriers) underlines that export diversification (supported by ‘aid for trade’) is crucial – as recognised in the analysis by the UN and NEPAD.</p>
		</div>
		
